<ce:para>In the paper, we emphasise some fundamental ideas that definitely are to be considered if a useful network backbone is to be built. Surprisingly often neglected constraint with considerable influence on the network backbone is network traffic. In the first part, paper suggests a formalised, practical approach to construction of the traffic matrix, which denotes the end to end traffic between all possible pairs of backbone access points. Second part of the paper deals with generating the initial backbone topology based on number of constraints. The paper extends the problem on the variable number of nodes in the designing procedure. Number and position of the nodes are denoted on the basis of various systematised topological constrains. As a conclusion, we suggest how to design a functioning backbone.</ce:para>
